{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"id":"a02321e8-dbd0-5297-868d-553f1e4ca57b","html":"<p><img src=\"/media/pixabay/solid-principle.jpg\" alt=\"Brief Statement of SOLID Principles\" title=\"Brief Statement of SOLID Principles\">\n<a href=\"https://pixabay.com/photos/brick-stone-blocks-1397278/\"><center><span style=\"color:black\">Image Source</span></center></a></p>\n<h2 id=\"s--single-responsibility-principle\"><a href=\"#s--single-responsibility-principle\" aria-label=\"s  single responsibility principle permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>S – Single Responsibility Principle</h2>\n<p>A class or module should have one and only one reason to change.</p>\n<h2 id=\"o--open-closed-principle\"><a href=\"#o--open-closed-principle\" aria-label=\"o  open closed principle permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>O – Open Closed Principle</h2>\n<p>Software entities (classes, modules, functions etc.) should be open for extension but closed for modification.</p>\n<h2 id=\"l--liskov-substitution-principle\"><a href=\"#l--liskov-substitution-principle\" aria-label=\"l  liskov substitution principle permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>L – Liskov Substitution Principle</h2>\n<p>Functions that use references of base classes must be able to use objects of the derived class without knowing it.</p>\n<h2 id=\"i--interface-segregation-principle\"><a href=\"#i--interface-segregation-principle\" aria-label=\"i  interface segregation principle permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>I – Interface Segregation Principle</h2>\n<p>Clients should not be forced to depend on methods they do not use.</p>\n<h2 id=\"d--dependency-inversion-principle\"><a href=\"#d--dependency-inversion-principle\" aria-label=\"d  dependency inversion principle permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>D – Dependency Inversion Principle</h2>\n<p>=> High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. Both should depend on abstractions.</p>\n<p>=> Abstractions should not depend on details, details should depend on abstractions.</p>","fields":{"slug":"/blog/2017/07/26/solid-principles","tagSlugs":["/tag/solid/","/tag/design-principle/"]},"frontmatter":{"date":"2017-07-26T22:40:32.169Z","description":"SOLID principle is one of the most well known principle in software community. It is intendent to make software designs more understandable, flexible and maintainable.","tags":["SOLID","Design Principle"],"title":"Brief Statement of SOLID Principles"}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"/blog/2017/07/26/solid-principles"}}